@nextghost this is not for arguing, but:
- the type of lock is not the same. An `UPDATE` locks the involved records just during the update, while `SELECT FOR UPDATE` locks the records between different operations, so IMHO everything else should wait until completion. For instance, in your example if you change the first line with a FOR UPDATE, thread B cannot update the record until A execute `update_record`. See https://www.postgresql.org/docs/9.5/static/sql-select.html#SQL-FOR-UPDATE-SHARE for more info about locking on postgres.
- `Table.__call__` simply select the first record using `first()`, so is barely an assurance of the fact there's just one record involved when we use it inside `update_or_insert`. It's simply the first corresponding to the query. Which is a debatable behavior. Is the first record in which order? And if you run an update_or_insert instruction with conditions that are not unique, then is the code which is wrong, not the library beyond.

Again, looking around I can't find any real cases where people are using `FOR UPDATE` to do an update or insert operation. On postgresql I would do something like this:

```sql
LOOP
    UPDATE sometable SET b = 'bar' WHERE a = 'foo';
    IF found THEN
        RETURN;
    END IF;
    BEGIN
        INSERT INTO sometable(a,b) VALUES ('foo', 'bar');
        RETURN;
    EXCEPTION WHEN unique_violation THEN
    END;
END LOOP;
```

on mysql I would do something like this:

```sql
INSERT 
    INTO sometable(a, b)
    VALUES ('foo', 'bar') 
    ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE
    a = 'foo', 
    b = 'bar';
```

and on any other database we support I have no idea.

@mdipierro I'm still to change `update_or_insert` to perform an update and an insert, avoiding the select. Seems the best behaviour to me. As @niphlod said, pydal is mainly used on web projects, so locking is not at option for me neither.

@marcoabreu If you think a parent folder for all pytest is necessary and reserved for future, I can take that. But isn’t pytest itself indicating python tests? IMO pytest is better than python-pytest as a parent folder name in this case. 

I always insist that a good naming and reasonable structure is critical to a project’ capability of maintenance and allow external contributors to better understand what has been done without asking “what is it?”. Therefore every decision had to be made with cautious otherwise it’s so hard to change later.

I understand your situation that some testing facility may already depend on this, if you insist, I can hold the change as it’s a minor issue. But I am afraid there will never be a good chance to fix it in the future

