@rstacruz at this point you've hit your limit for storage in Ceph. I could not find anything on Ceph's documentation on freeing up disk space. In that case, you'll probably want to provision a new cluster with a larger EBS for ceph. There could be something else in http://docs.ceph.com/docs/hammer/rados/operations/add-or-rm-osds/ that I might be missing which could help with managing the cluster, but in the end if you're likely to hit this 300GB limit it's better to expand your EBS drives backing Ceph.

Assuming you're using AWS, we provision one EBS with 100GB of storage for each instance, for a grand total of 300GB (as seen in https://github.com/deis/deis/issues/4943#issuecomment-190382861). You can bump that using the documentation [here](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/installing_deis/aws/#customize-cloudformation-json) to bump DockerVolumeSize to a higher limit.

Unfortunately since this cluster was created using CloudFormation, we cannot de-provision and create a new EBS for each instance as CloudFormation will just re-provision a new volume with the same size and re-mount it to the instance when you terminate the old one.

