And under the hood SoS just copy all text from `template`, update it with whatever new in `[default]` and execute it. No nested workflow is necessry. Using `sos_run` seems to messed up the DAG. For example in my previous thread, the first DAG looks like:

```
strict digraph "" {
template1_0;
}
```
but it should in fact look like my 2nd DAG:

```
strict digraph "" {
default_0;
"main2 ['2.txt']";
"main4 ['4.txt']";
"main1 ['1.txt']";
"main3 ['3.txt']";
"main2 ['2.txt']" -> default_0;
"main4 ['4.txt']" -> default_0;
"main1 ['1.txt']" -> "main2 ['2.txt']";
"main3 ['3.txt']" -> "main4 ['4.txt']";
}
```

Presumably we'd allow `-t` as shorthand for `--template` and support passing URL templates via this flag.

Do we want `pulumi up` to be consistent with `pulumi new`, e.g. `pulumi up -t <url>`, or is the "installable cloud app" concept different enough to warrant `pulumi up <url>`?

@joeduffy, @lukehoban, thoughts?

@Shahzadfarukh100 No, I rewrote the code that was triggering the bug to avoid using `{% crispy_field %}` tag altogether, because even though this is an actual bug and I even wrote tests for it, maintainers are not willing to include my fix.

I'm not sure if I should waste 1-2 hours of my time to verify if this bug still happen in Django 2.1 (most probably it does) if it's not going to be merged anyway.

I think everybody should simply avoid using `{% crispy_field %}`. I guess almost nobody uses it anyway or it would be reported earlier.

Thanks @rctauber!

@dustine32: ROBOT is independent of OWLTools. In theory you could run it as a pre-processing step in the load process, this may be necessary for some ontologies, but in general it's good to request the changes upstream so everyone benefits.

You can get metadata on any OBO ontology, including what the tracker is, from http://obofoundry.org/ (@rctauber and I are part of a project that maintains this). Every ontology the Alliance uses should be listed here.

